            <div type="translation">
                <p><!--Tentative translation resp="#TA"> 
                    ...(to) [-]ianus [the curator kalendarii, 'the curator of the account-books'?, the office which?] he adminstrated with true loyalty [at the same time as] 
                    (being) the curator portensis kalendarii (i.e. something to do with overseeing the accounts of port expenses or taxes?), office which he [conducted with] 
                    exceptional [diligence]; the praiseworthy munerarius, who with the sacred indulgence (of the emperor?) organised public games, which 
                    he was worthy of as expected (*I'm not at all sure about the optando here, perhaps as an ablative of respect, 'in respect to the desired/expected'?*) and which he wanted,
                    and he gave back to all the citizens a most pleasing production which for [... days and many hours held the people] in the pleasures of theatre, and [then the whole
                    crowd] in their merriness moved [to the arena at] midday, where it marvelled at the most distinguished [(display of the) prepared arrangements....every] type of 
                    plant-eating animals and oriental beasts; and, having sat down, from midday the crowd in both auditoria [enjoyed] varied types of entertainment. [And likewise
                    thanks to] the sacred indulgence (of the emperor), he proved himself particularly worthy as he invited all his fellow citizens to the most elegant [banquet which he had provided
                    for] with the most splendid abundance. When the people, on account of the public shows (he had) virtuously organised, demanded with very frequent pleads that two-horse chariot
                    statues (be erected) in each centurial district for this most excellent man in order to increase his honours, he in his modesty [was content] with 
                    two chariot-statues and [three?] equestrian [statues...] --></p>
            </div>
